Terms of Trade is a daily newsletter that untangles a world embroiled in trade wars. Sign up here. The U.S. and China agreed to another truce in their trade dispute on Saturday in Japan. Unlike the previous meeting in Argentina, this time the two sides’ statements are reasonably similar. But there remain some substantial differences, including on whether China agreed to make immediate purchases of U.S. farm goods, and whether the freeze in new U.S. tariffs is permanent. Here is a side-by-side comparison of the main points of the two statements: — With assistance by James Mayger, and Miao Han